element.name: Phoenix Park - White's Gate by Lahtac, Traditional Cache (1/1.5)
element.description:
Dublin’s Phoenix Park is a treasure with more than 1700 acres of walled parkland just 3km from the centre of the city.
At 707 hectares (1752 acres) is one of the largest enclosed recreational spaces within any European capital city.

long-description.p: Few cities have such a facility on their doorsteps – it is more than twice as large as Central Park in New York.
The park was for centuries the property of the King’s representatives in Ireland, used as a Royal hunting park – which is why it was enclosed by a wall, to keep the game in.
However it was opened to the public in 1747 and so for more than 250 years has been a favourite playground for generations of Dubliners.
The park is open all year round, there is no admission charge and visitors can explore freely.
The nearest gate to the cache location is pedestrian only access point beside Farmleigh which is an estate of 78 acres situated to the north-west of the park.
However the cache location is accessible from any entrance point to the park.
The cache is located on a trek adjacent to the gate keeper’s lodge.

Parking is freely available on Whites Road leading up to the gate. N53.21.992 W06.21.180 and on Chesterfield Avenue at N53.22.166 W06.20.885 where the final location is a pleasent walk away off road on a flat treelined track

element.additional-waypoints:
CR27C2G - Parking Location 1
N 53° 21.992 W 006° 21.180
This is the nearest parking location on Whites Road to the final destination. The cache is just off road on a flat track.
PK27C2G - Parking Location 2
N 53° 22.166 W 006° 20.885
Parking is available at this location at the side of the road. The final location is just a pleasent walk along a treelined track.
